  "body": "**System information**\r\nGeth 1.10.3-stable-d33ce83c\r\nUbuntu 20.04.2 LTS\r\n\r\n**Description**\r\nStarted clean geth with `--syncmode snap` , it synced well and later built states.\r\n\r\nThen, when it reached recent blocks, it started having `BAD BLOCK` messages due to `invalid bloom` error. It then `Rewinding blockchain` back to last snapshot, then recalculates states. \r\n\r\nFull error message: \r\n[eth_invalid_bloom.txt](https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/files/6610929/eth_invalid_bloom.txt)\r\n\r\nAfter rewinding, geth also prints -\r\n```\r\nWARN [06-07|17:20:41.658] Rolled back chain segment                header=12588676->12586627 fast=12588611->12586627 block=12588611->0 reason=\"syncing canceled (requested)\"\r\nWARN [06-07|17:20:41.658] Synchronisation failed, dropping peer    peer=08b33cb2c00692aea404af3892904a6de79b1729354ea4c90fcafbd144281b68 err=\"retrieved hash chain is invalid: invalid bloom (remote: 157e11a7c10c1013b43315dae340de0f5b861aa3bcd0a1a4240568d9d462cd02c0a55d64a1dc1792c084dac00f900bf72ba0d04a692328adceb2a\r\\r\nfa10d4e652bab5ec3575ab2b1d649c648a645e2a01b8f5bc106a554067c6ce4a78001e0178fc9506  local: 157e11a7c10c3c93b47315dee3c1de0f7b871ae7bcd0e1e6bf0579dbd462cd0ac0a75d64a1dc1796c684dbd2af9ccbf72ba8d04a7d672aadceb2bf6a06a89f8a7a6460b048062f7ecb7f3e0d5dec7ee6069be04c8bd37e2cf5a747d4daced73c9cab8b923be2ef0d943e1a1234d31fd7f6\r\n4025fe475a8decc2bd4dbc77887706ec6aa6a7cf7e7175f2cf01488d21ce7cecc5dda5edf5e38e6a6b77cf2ef5e9fe2fbf343dbbfca110f256eabbeb02b9cd5cd05c0d507b6dea3e6fb6af5a7a99f6ebdd074e65f6c442392d4ff4403e9dd6dd6157c75b6ddb1ffa18f4e6d2babdfd3575efeb9d64dc648ae55e3a45f8f5bc146a55e867c6ce6afd109e897cfd9d06)\"\r\nERROR[06-07|17:20:41.659] Ethereum peer removal failed             peer=08b33cb2         err=\"peer not registered\"\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe next time, it'll happen on a different block, couple of blocks ahead. These bad block messages occur **every 5-30** blocks so far. For a day now, it's 200-600 blocks from head, **these frequent rewinds prevent geth from reaching full sync mode**. \r\n\r\nDoes this happen due to error on a different node or a malicious actor?\r\n",
